(31, 'broiler_business', 'BROILER VALUE CHAIN IN NIGERIA', 'broiler, business, value chain,', '2018-06-25', 'busayo', '11246929chick-929566_1920.jpg', '<p>DESCRIPTION OF THE INDUSTRY</p><p>The Nigerian poultry industry is estimated at N80 billion ($600million). The estimated poultry meat consumption in Nigeria is approximately 1.2 MT, as at 2013. It has the second largest chicken population after South Africas 200 million birds.</p><p>A value chain describes the full range of activities which are required to bring a product or service from conception, through the different phases of production, (involving a combination of physical transformation and the input of various producer services) delivery to final consumers, and final disposal after use. Caplinsey and Morris (2002).</p><p>The broiler industry in Nigeria is made up of broiler farmers, input suppliers, transport/logistics companies, wholesalers and retailers.</p><p><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" data-filename=\"image.png\" style=\"width: 624px;\"><br></p><p><b>EMPLOYMENT</b></p><p>It is estimated that broiler hatchery and rearing industries employ over 100,000 people, the processing sector employs a total of 35,000 people, and the broiler distribution industries employ 6,000 people. The grand total of employment within the broiler industry is 141, 000 employees. </p><p>There are three important levels within a value chain, these are: chain actors (deals directly with the product), supporters and chain influencers. They invest time, effort and money; build relationships with other actors to reach a common goal. We can conveniently refer to them as stakeholders in the value chain.<span style=\"font-family: \" times=\"\" new=\"\" roman\",=\"\" serif;=\"\" text-align:=\"\" justify;\"=\"\"></span></p>'),
(32, 'broiler_business', 'BROILER VALUE CHAIN IN NIGERIA', 'broiler, business, value chain,', '2018-06-25', 'busayo', '42839388poultry-farm-1544654_640.jpg', '');

